               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160529-110-person999">
                  JOHN 
                  LEY
               <interp inst="t18160529-110-person999" type="surname" value="LEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160529-110-person999" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160529-110-person999" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 2nd of April last, I was an inspector of the River. In consequence of information I received, I caused the prisoner at the bar to be stopped; he was on board the Lord Castlereagh as an <rs id="t18160529-110-deflabel588" type="occupation">exciseman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18160529-110-defend997 t18160529-110-deflabel588"></join>; I was at <placeName id="t18160529-110-crimeloc589">the East India Dock</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18160529-110-crimeloc589" type="placeName" value="the East India Dock"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18160529-110-crimeloc589" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18160529-110-off586 t18160529-110-crimeloc589"></join>-gate. On searching the prisoner, I took the pepper mentioned in the indictment out of his pockets and hat. I asked him how he came by it, and he said, it was done, and could not be helped; he said nothing more then. I happened to be on board the Castlereagh on that day, and I saw the prisoner on board. Her cargo was pepper.</p>
               <p>
            
